.IX Title "Plagger::Plugin::Subscription::Bloglines 3"
.TH Plagger::Plugin::Subscription::Bloglines 3 "2006-12-05" "perl v5.8.9" "User Contributed Perl Documentation"
.SH "NAME"
Plagger::Plugin::Subscription::Bloglines \- Bloglines Subscription
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 5
\&  - module: Subscription::Bloglines
\&    config:
\&      username: your-email@account
\&      password: your-password
\&      mark_read: 1
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This plugin allows you to synchronize your subscription using
Bloglines Web Services sync \s-1API\s0.
.SH "CONFIGURATION"
.IX Header "CONFIGURATION"
.IP "username, password" 4
.IX Item "username, password"
Your username & password to use with Bloglines \s-1API\s0.
.IP "mark_read" 4
.IX Item "mark_read"
\&\f(CW\*(C`mark_read\*(C'\fR specifies whether this plugin \fImarks as read\fR the items
you synchronize. With this option set to 0, you will get the
duplicated updates every time you run Plagger, until you mark them
unread using Bloglines browser interface. Defaults to 1.
.Sp
For people who uses Bloglines browser interface regularly, and use
Plagger as a tool to synchronize feed updates to mobile devices (like
\&\s-1PSP\s0 or iPod), I'd recommend set this option to 0.
.Sp
Otherwise, especially for Publish::Gmail plugin users, I recommend set
to 1, the default.
.IP "fetch_meta" 4
.IX Item "fetch_meta"
\&\f(CW\*(C`fetch_meta\*(C'\fR specifies whether this plugin fetches \fIfolder\fR
structure using listsubs \s-1API\s0. With this option on, all feeds under
\&\fIPlagger\fR folder will have \fIPlagger\fR as its tag.
.Sp
You can use this tags information using Rules in later phase.
.IP "dont_use_notifier_api" 4
.IX Item "dont_use_notifier_api"
Turn it on when you want to skip Notifier \s-1API\s0, which could sometimes
be broken and always returns 0 instead of the actual unread count.
